etymologies: late Middle English: from medieval Latin, ‘forewarn’, from Latin praemonere, from prae ‘beforehand’ + monere ‘warn’. The term comes from praemunire facias ‘that you warn (a person to appear)’, part of the wording in the writ

definitions: the offense of asserting or maintaining papal jurisdiction in England.
shortDefinitions: offence of asserting or maintaining papal jurisdiction in England

definitions: a writ charging a sheriff to summon a person accused of this offense.
shortDefinitions: writ charging sheriff to summon person accused of this offence
